00:00:00.368 --> 00:00:02.387
&gt;&gt;Now that we figured
out the total revenue

00:00:02.387 --> 00:00:04.486
given any quantity,

00:00:04.486 --> 00:00:07.374
and we've also been able to
express it algebraically,

00:00:07.374 --> 00:00:09.935
I want to think about what
the marginal revenue is

00:00:09.935 --> 00:00:12.004
at any one of these points.

00:00:12.004 --> 00:00:13.225
To think about marginal revenue,

00:00:13.225 --> 00:00:14.679
marginal revenue is just how much does our

00:00:14.679 --> 00:00:16.009
total revenue change,

00:00:16.009 --> 00:00:18.977
given some change in our quantity.

00:00:18.977 --> 00:00:20.460
Then later, we can use that

00:00:20.460 --> 00:00:23.335
so that we can optimize the profit

00:00:23.335 --> 00:00:25.081
for our monopoly over here.

00:00:25.281 --> 00:00:27.379
I'm going to try to do
it without calculus.

00:00:27.379 --> 00:00:28.849
It actually would be very straightforward

00:00:28.849 --> 00:00:29.594
to do it with calculus

00:00:29.594 --> 00:00:30.878
because we're essentially
just trying to find

00:00:30.878 --> 00:00:33.353
the slope at any point along this curve,

00:00:33.353 --> 00:00:34.822
but I'll try to do it algebraically

00:00:34.822 --> 00:00:36.322
and maybe it will even
give you a little intuition

00:00:36.322 --> 00:00:39.262
for what we end up doing
eventually in calculus.

00:00:39.339 --> 00:00:40.669
The first thing I want to do

00:00:40.669 --> 00:00:42.004
is essentially find the slope,

00:00:42.004 --> 00:00:43.689
the slope right over here.

00:00:43.689 --> 00:00:46.017
The best way to find the
slope right over here is say

00:00:46.017 --> 00:00:48.983
how much does my total revenue change

00:00:48.983 --> 00:00:51.348
if I have a very small change in quantity?

00:00:51.348 --> 00:00:53.817
If I have a very small change in quantity,

00:00:53.817 --> 00:00:56.831
how much does my total revenue change?

00:00:56.831 --> 00:00:58.523
Let me think about it this way.

00:00:58.523 --> 00:01:00.298
The other ones I will
be able to approximate

00:01:00.298 --> 00:01:02.059
a little bit easier.

00:01:02.059 --> 00:01:03.188
Let's think of it this way.

00:01:03.188 --> 00:01:06.336
If my quantity is 0,

00:01:06.336 --> 00:01:09.106
my total revenue is 0.

00:01:09.106 --> 00:01:10.037
That one's easy.

00:01:10.037 --> 00:01:11.535
If I increase my quantity

00:01:11.535 --> 00:01:13.473
very, very, very, very little,

00:01:13.473 --> 00:01:16.843
so let's just make it 0.001,

00:01:16.843 --> 00:01:18.983
what is going to be my total revenue?

00:01:18.983 --> 00:01:21.027
We could think about it
in terms of this curve

00:01:21.027 --> 00:01:22.003
right over here,

00:01:22.003 --> 00:01:23.863
or we could just use this expression,

00:01:23.863 --> 00:01:26.701
which we derived from
price times quantity,

00:01:26.701 --> 00:01:27.959
and we will get,

00:01:27.959 --> 00:01:30.432
I'll get my calculator out,

00:01:30.987 --> 00:01:33.625
if our quantity is .001,

00:01:33.625 --> 00:01:36.848
our total revenue is
going to be negative ...

00:01:36.848 --> 00:01:38.510
Let me turn the calculator on.

00:01:38.510 --> 00:01:44.286
Total revenue is going to be -.001²,

00:01:44.286 --> 00:01:45.201
squared,

00:01:45.201 --> 00:01:46.377
so that's that part,

00:01:46.377 --> 00:01:49.377
plus 6 times .001,

00:01:49.377 --> 00:01:53.855
6 times .001.

00:01:53.855 --> 00:01:55.816
That's going to be our total revenue.

00:01:55.816 --> 00:01:59.722
It's going to be 0.005999.

00:01:59.722 --> 00:02:05.002
It's 0.00599.

00:02:05.002 --> 00:02:06.116
Now we can figure out

00:02:06.116 --> 00:02:07.794
or get a pretty good approximation

00:02:07.794 --> 00:02:10.018
for that marginal revenue
right at that point.

00:02:10.018 --> 00:02:13.792
Our change in quantity is .001,

00:02:13.792 --> 00:02:18.976
so our ΔQ, this right over here is 0.001.

00:02:18.976 --> 00:02:20.536
That's our change in quantity,

00:02:20.536 --> 00:02:25.703
and our change in revenue is 0.00599,

00:02:25.703 --> 00:02:27.711
and so we just have to divide.

00:02:27.711 --> 00:02:31.811
We just have to divide
.005999, that top one,

00:02:31.811 --> 00:02:33.433
our change in total revenue

00:02:33.433 --> 00:02:34.982
divided by our change in quantity,

00:02:34.982 --> 00:02:38.388
divided by .001.

00:02:38.388 --> 00:02:42.416
We get 5.99999.

00:02:42.416 --> 00:02:44.198
If you try it with even smaller numbers,

00:02:44.198 --> 00:02:47.756
if you tried this with .00000001,

00:02:47.756 --> 00:02:49.018
you'll get 5-point,

00:02:49.018 --> 00:02:51.059
and you'll get even more 9s going on.

00:02:51.059 --> 00:02:52.220
The closer that you get,

00:02:52.220 --> 00:02:54.004
the smaller your change in,

00:02:54.004 --> 00:02:56.018
and this is what you
essentially do in calculus.

00:02:56.018 --> 00:02:58.656
You try to find a super
small change right over here.

00:02:58.656 --> 00:03:01.021
This is essentially going to be 6.

00:03:01.021 --> 00:03:02.718
Our marginal revenue at this point

00:03:02.718 --> 00:03:04.556
is essentially going to be 6.

00:03:04.556 --> 00:03:05.608
What I want to do is I'm going to plot

00:03:05.608 --> 00:03:08.551
marginal revenue here on
our demand curve as well

00:03:08.551 --> 00:03:09.712
or on this axis

00:03:09.712 --> 00:03:11.956
where we've already
plotted our demand curve.

00:03:11.956 --> 00:03:14.190
When our quantity is 0,

00:03:14.190 --> 00:03:15.382
our marginal revenue,

00:03:15.382 --> 00:03:17.184
if we just barely increase quantity,

00:03:17.184 --> 00:03:19.511
the incremental total revenue we get

00:03:19.511 --> 00:03:21.131
is going to be 6.

00:03:21.131 --> 00:03:22.646
I'll just plot it.

00:03:22.646 --> 00:03:24.000
I'll just plot it right over there.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:25.299
That makes sense.

00:03:25.299 --> 00:03:27.452
The marginal benefit in the market is 6,

00:03:27.452 --> 00:03:28.151
right at that point.

00:03:28.151 --> 00:03:30.454
If we were to just sell
a drop of orange juice

00:03:30.454 --> 00:03:32.577
or I guess we're selling
oranges in this case,

00:03:32.577 --> 00:03:33.415
not juice,

00:03:33.415 --> 00:03:35.740
but if we were to sell
a millionth of a pound

00:03:35.740 --> 00:03:36.947
of oranges,

00:03:36.947 --> 00:03:39.218
we would get the equivalent of roughly

00:03:39.218 --> 00:03:42.380
$6 per pound for that millionth of a pound

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:43.833
because that's the marginal benefit

00:03:43.833 --> 00:03:47.158
for that very first
incremental chunk of orange

00:03:47.158 --> 00:03:48.087
out there in the market,

00:03:48.087 --> 00:03:50.026
so it makes complete sense.

00:03:50.026 --> 00:03:52.028
Now let's think about the
slope at these other points.

00:03:52.028 --> 00:03:53.312
These, I'm going to approximate.

00:03:53.312 --> 00:03:54.622
I could do it this way,

00:03:54.622 --> 00:03:56.519
but I'll just approximate it.

00:03:56.519 --> 00:03:58.343
I'll just approximate it
by using other points.

00:03:58.343 --> 00:04:00.565
If I want to find the
slope right over here,

00:04:00.565 --> 00:04:02.535
when our quantity is equal to 1,

00:04:02.535 --> 00:04:03.988
the slope would look like,

00:04:03.988 --> 00:04:05.770
the slope would look like that.

00:04:05.770 --> 00:04:07.053
I'm going to approximate it

00:04:07.053 --> 00:04:10.190
by finding the slope
between these two points.

00:04:10.190 --> 00:04:11.706
I am going to approximate it,

00:04:11.706 --> 00:04:12.588
and actually, it's going to be

00:04:12.588 --> 00:04:13.841
a very good approximation.

00:04:13.841 --> 00:04:15.034
I'll do it later with calculus

00:04:15.034 --> 00:04:16.773
to show that it is a
very good approximation.

